        "text": "Genesis 10:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and the Revelation of John (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 4:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); not, however, as throne-bearers or throne-holders, or as forming the chariot of the throne, but as occupying the highest place as living beings (חיּות, ζῷα) in the realm of spirits, standing by the side of God as the heavenly King when He comes to judgment, and proclaiming the majesty of the Judge of the world. In this character God stationed them on the eastern side of paradise, not \"to inhabit the garden as the temporary representatives of man,\" but \"to keep the way of the tree of life,\" i.e., to render it impossible for man to return to paradise, and eat of the tree of life. Hence there appeared by their side the flame of a sword, apparently in constant motion, cutting hither and thither, representing the devouring fire of the divine wrath, and showing the cherubim to be ministers of judgment. With the expulsion of man from the garden of Eden, paradise itself vanished from the earth. God did not withdraw from the tree of life its supernatural power, nor did He destroy the garden before their eyes, but simply prevented their return, to show that it should be preserved until the time of the end, when sin should be rooted out by the judgment, and death abolished by the Conqueror of the serpent (",
